## Key Terms Summary

| Term | Simple definition |
|---|---|
| SOC | Team that monitors and defends company security 24/7 |
| SIEM | Tool that collects all logs and shows alerts in one dashboard |
| Ticket | A logged alert or task that needs analyst investigation |
| True positive | Alert is real — an actual threat exists |
| False positive | Alert is a false alarm — no real threat |
| IP reputation check | Looking up an IP to see if it's known to be malicious |
| IOC | Indicator of Compromise — evidence of an attack (IP, domain, file hash) |
| Escalation | Passing a confirmed or complex alert to a higher-level analyst |
| Containment | Actions taken to stop a threat from spreading |
| Playbook | Pre-written step-by-step response procedure for common attack types |

---

## Personal notes / things I want to remember

- The SIEM shows alerts but doesn't explain them — that's the analyst's job
- Always check an IP on multiple tools, not just one
- Outbound traffic to a bad IP is often more serious than inbound (it may mean
  a device is already infected and calling home)
- Never act alone on a major finding — document and escalate
- False positives are normal and expected; good analysts tune them over time

